<TEXT>
the western shoshone indians have vowed to 
press their claim to full grazing rights on a halfmillion acres of 
land despite an appeals court ruling limiting the number of horses 
and cows they can have 
this isnt the end to litigation we dont consider this issue 
resolved said thomas e leubben attorney for the western 
shoshone national council only congress can resolve the western 
shoshone land issue 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals on wednesday reversed us 
district judge bruce thompsons september 1986 order that gave 
sisters mary and carrie dann members of the shoshone tribe the 
right to graze cattle and horses at their 180acre ranch in 
northcentral nevadas crescent valley 
thompson had ruled the danns had aboriginal and treaty rights to 
graze their livestock on 530000 acres without being regulated by 
federal agencies or paying grazing fees 
the appellate ruling limits the danns to grazing 26 cows and 79 
horses the number their parents had on the land when the 1934 
taylor grazing act took effect the sisters currently have 768 cows 
and 850 horses 
a tearful carrie dann said at a news conference monday she has no 
plans to reduce the herd 
im not really afraid of going to jail because i believe im 
right she said 
the us government sued the danns for trespassing in 1974 to 
prevent them from using the land for grazing the 14yearold case 
has been argued three times in federal court in reno twice in the 
appeals court and once before the us supreme court 
the sisters claim that an 1863 treaty with the united states 
gives them the right to use the land for grazing 
the government contends that the western shoshone lost its 
ancestral land in 1979 when the indian claims commission awarded the 
tribe 26 million for the acreage the indians have refused to 
accept the money 
this land was never given by the united states to us it is the 
creators land carrie dann said monday 
the creator put us on this land she said we were not placed 
here by the united states government our livelihood is tied to this 
land they wanted to do away with our livelihood theyre trying to 
destroy our beliefs our culture 
luebben of albuquerque nm said he would continue to argue 
the case in federal court but added he would try other avenues 
considering this decision by the 9th circuit court of appeals 
the shoshone people are going to have to appeal to the public and to 
congress luebben said 
we consider this decision to be wrong and extremely unjust 
he said there is still institutional racism in the united 
states 
