<TEXT>
citing new evidence the government has reopened 
the case of four people jailed for life in two 1974 bombings of 
british pubs that killed seven people including three soldiers and 
injured 91 
the bombings occurred during a wave of ira terrorism and 
champions of the guildford four said the government had in its 
zeal to obtain convictions ignored evidence that pointed to other 
suspects 
the irish government welcomed mondays decision and the times of 
london said in an editorial today that it was as difficult as it 
was wise 
responding to pressure that made the case a cause celebre in 
britain and ireland home secretary douglas hurd told parliament 
monday that new information had emerged meriting that the case be 
heard by the court of appeal 
carole richardson 31 patrick armstrong 36 paul hill 34 and 
gerry conlon 33 were convicted of planting bombs in two pubs 
frequented by british soldiers in guildford a town southwest of 
london in october 1974 five people including two soldiers were 
killed and 65 injured 
armstrong and hill also were convicted of a pub bombing in the 
london suburb of woolwich a month later in which the bartender and a 
soldier died and 26 people were injured 
all four were sentenced to life imprisonment in october 1975 and 
two years later a court rejected their appeal 
in a written reply to a lawmakers question hurd said he was 
satisfied that there are new and substantial points which clearly 
are best considered by the court 
these he said included apparent alibis for hill and miss 
richardson that had never been put to a court and indications that 
miss richardson was injected with drugs during her interrogation and 
suffering symptoms of withdrawal from barbiturates 
the possible effects of these drugs on the reliability of her 
statements were not adequately exposed to the jury or the court of 
appeal hurd said 
however hurd declined to act on a point of law raised by two 
senior british judges who have argued that the appeals court ruled 
against the four despite being aware of confessions by two irish 
republican army men to the bombings 
the irish government in a statement said it has consistently 
conveyed the serious concern about the guildford four case to the 
british authorities grant mckee coauthor of time bomb a 
recent book on the case said we are very gratified that this is 
the first official recognition of the justifiable concern about this 
case which has attracted people of the eminence of two archbishops 
