<TEXT>
the supreme court today set aside a ruling that 
limited the access enjoyed by labor unions that represent federal 
government employees to the home addresses of all their members 
the justices told a federal appeals court to restudy its ruling 
that requires federal agencies to give employees an opportunity to 
have their addresses withheld from their union 
the federal labor relations authority decided in two cases that 
denying the unions access to the information is an unfair labor 
practice but the 8th us circuit court of appeals limited the 
authoritys decision in a ruling last january 
the appeals court said that although unions generally are 
entitled to the addresses the information may not be disclosed 
without the employees consent 
in a brief order today the justices set aside the 8th circuit 
courts ruling and ordered the appeals court to restudy the two 
cases in light of regulations published by the two federal agencies 
involved 
in one case the american federation of government employees 
sought the names and home addresses of some 900 union members who 
work for the farmers home administration finance office in st 
louis in the second case the national federation of federal 
employees asked for names and addresses of members who work for the 
defense departments mapping agency aerospace center in st louis 
the unions said they needed the home addresses to communicate 
with members in the privacy of their homes about pending collective 
bargaining negotiations the unions also said the information could 
help them in recruiting new members 
the federal labor relations authority said disclosing the 
information does not violate workers privacy rights 
but the 8th circuit court said we doubt that the public 
interest would be served in any way by imposing disclosure of the 
names and addresses on employees who regard that information as 
private and who do not choose to receive union communications at 
home 
the fela asked the justices to overturn the appeals courts 
ruling 
in another development justice department lawyers told the high 
court that the reagan administration is seeking to resolve the 
problem by taking steps to provide the unions in both cases with the 
information they seek 
the justice department lawyers said they believe government 
agencies should be allowed to withhold the names and addresses but 
that providing the information is a better solution in these cases 
they said requiring agencies to get the consent of employees 
before giving such information to the unions violates federal law 
the consent requirment could mean that the government will be 
threatened with lawsuits anytime it gives out even innocuous 
information about federal employees the justice department lawyers 
said 
they said the justices should order the 8th circuit court to 
reconsider its decision in light of the steps being taken to provide 
the unions with the names and addresses they seek 
the case is federal labor relations authority vs us department 
of agriculture 88349 
</TEXT>
