suit against the government 
the suit was filed by 189 families in dallas who live near three 
lead smelters operated by rsr corp dixie metals corp and nl 
industries 
they sought damages under the federal tort claims act which 
allows citizens to sue the government in some circumstances 
the dallas families said members have suffered brain damage 
developmental defects and lifelong debilitating effects from 
lead pollution 
their suit said john hernandez deputy administrator of the 
environmental protection agency was negligent because he ordered 
further study of the problem rather than an immediate cleanup after 
a congressional hearing in 1983 found high levels of lead in soil 
and in schoolchildrens blood samples 
the us circuit court of appeals here last july upheld a federal 
judges ruling that dismissed the case 
the appeals court said hernandezs decision to order further 
study was a discretionary policymaking action immune from suit 
under the tort claims act 
the plaintiffs said hernandezs decision was based only upon 
scientific considerations that did not involve the exercise of such 
discretion 
but the appeals court said hernandez based his decision on 
economic social and political policy considerations making his 
choice immune from suit 
for example hernandez said he was concerned that a cleanup 
would set a precedent for other areas of the nation he also said 
that failure to order further study would expose him to criticism he 
acted too hastily 
one of the smelters made a pollution cleanup offer but 
hernandez said he was reluctant to accept the offer without 
additional study because the cleanup might be inadequate 
the case is wells vs us 88653 
