<TEXT>
key events in solidarity history 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
aug 14 electrician lech walesa leads an occupation stike at 
gdansks lenin shipyard and starts a worker revolt against the 
communist state 
aug 31 legal registration makes solidarity the soviet blocs 
only independent union during its 16 months of legal activity 
solidarity membership will grow to an estimated 10 million and a 
sense of renewal will sweep the nation 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
dec 13 martial law is declared by polish leader gen wojciech 
jaruzelski solidarity activities are suppressed and thousands of 
members are interned including walesa 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
oct 8 solidarity is banned and an official trade union 
alliance is created to take its place president reagan expands us 
economic sanctions against poland by suspending its most favored 
trade status 
nov 11 walesa is freed 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
july 22 jaruzelski lifts martial law but leaves many 
restrictive edicts 
oct 5 walesa wins the nobel peace prize 
oct 3 the government steps up pressure on key activists still 
underground and offers 11 in prison including advisers to walesa 
oneway passports out of the country to avoid trial on sedition 
charges 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
july 21 an amnesty is approved for political prisoners 
including the 11 prominent union leaders jailed after the 
martiallaw crackdown 
oct 19 the popular prosolidarity priest the rev jerzy 
popieluszko is slain four state security police will be tried and 
convicted in the murder 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
aug 31 walesa accuses the government of presiding over a 
political economic and cultural disaster as supporters nationwide 
mark the fifth anniversary of solidaritys birth 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
sept 11 the government orders the release of 225 political 
prisoners including all senior solidarity leaders 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
feb 19 reagan lifts the last of us sanctions against poland 
nov 29 poles vote in first referendum in 41 years but deny 
government support for economic reform package 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
april 24may 10 strikes hit steel mills shipyards and other 
plants across poland police break up one strike others gradually 
die out 
aug 16 workers declare a strike at the july manifesto coal 
mine in jasztrebie in a pay dispute the strikes spread creating 
polands worst wave of labor strife in seven years 
aug 26 interior minister gen czeslaw kiszczak proposes talks 
with workers laying the groundwork for a possible government 
meeting with walesa 
aug 31 on the eighth anniversary of the legalization of 
solidarity walesa holds his first meeting with government officials 
in six years and appeals to workers to end strikes 
sept 3 july manifesto miners end their strike 
sept 19 the government led by prime minister zbigniew messner 
resigns amid sharp criticism of its management of the economy 
sept 27 parliament names micezyslaw f rakowski as prime 
minister 
oct 25 the talks are postponed as government objects to two 
opposition participants 
oct 31 government announces plans to close lenin shipyard in 
gdansk as unprofitable 
nov 30 walesa holds an unprecedented live tv debate with 
alfred miodowicz head of the official trade union walesa is hailed 
as the victor and government polls show support for legalizing 
solidarity on the rise 
dec 2021 at the first part of a party plenum central 
committee members are instructed to poll the party rankandfile for 
their attitude toward solidarity 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
jan 4 the government plans price increases of 20 percent and 
hopes to hold overall inflation to 50 percent 
jan 13 a party source says the government is willing to 
restore solidaritys legal status if it joins in political and 
economic reforms 
jan 16 at the second part of a party plenum central committee 
members debate whether polands future includes trade union 
pluralism 
jan 17 rakowski urges the party to legalize solidarity on 
condition it not be a government opponent that would pull the 
country into anarchy 
</TEXT>
