<TEXT>
latin american nations must negotiate debt 
reduction agreements with commercial bank creditors or face a 
worsening economic situation that could lead to the return of 
military dictatorships in the region a panel of experts said 
tuesday 
the negotiation recommendation was made in a report by the 
interamerican dialogue a grouping of 66 prominent citizens from 
the united states canada latin america and the caribbean 
another key recommendation was for the incoming bush 
administration in washington and leaders of other industrialized 
countries to actively encourage debt reduction agreements and to 
provide appropriate financial guarantees to support such 
initiatives 
six years after the debt crisis began latin america remains 
mired in depression the group said in its 59page report 
unemployment and underemployment are at record levels it 
said wages have declined sharply by as much as 50 percent in 
some places average income per capita has fallen back to the level 
of 1978 and is not recovering 
the report the americas in 1989 consensus for action said 
the alternative for latin america to decisive action is a 
treadmill of austerity stagnation and rising debt 
it said the crisis could condemn latin america to a long period 
of economic hardship and political turbulence 
in some countries civilian authorities may be forced to yield 
to military rule thus reversing a strong trend over the past 
decade toward elected government it said 
the report also recommended that 
the nations of latin america revamp development strategies 
restructure their economies and effectively integrate them in the 
world economy 
the united states address its own economic problems and join 
other industrial countries to reduce international financial 
imbalances open world markets and sustain world growth 
the international financial institutions including the world 
bank sharply step up lending to latin america provided the debtor 
governments adhere to economic reform programs 
the cochairmen of the report panel were sol linowitz a former 
ambassador to the organization of american states and a negotiator 
of the panama canal treaties and former costa rican president 
daniel oduber 
also on the ideologically diverse panel were former presidents 
nicolas ardito barletta of panama and osvaldo hurtado of ecuador and 
numerous former cabinet ministers from the united states and latin 
america 
the report listed the hemispheres major debtors as brazil 
argentina mexico chile venezuela and colombia they account for 
85 percent of the regions debt 
since 1985 us policy on latin americas foreign debt has been 
guided by the socalled baker plan named for former treasury 
secretary and now secretary of statedesignate james a baker iii 
the plan calls for increased lending by commercial banks to latin 
america in return for economic restructuring but lending levels 
since 1985 have been far below expectations 
a month ago presidentelect bush indicated he will undertake a 
major review of us policy toward third world debt because of the 
enormous problems facing latin america 
on central america the report called on the united states to end 
its diplomatic boycott of the sandinista government and bilaterally 
negotiate mutual security arrangements saying there can be no 
double standard the report also argued that managua must desist 
from assisting insurgencies in el salvador and elsewhere 
on drug trafficking the report said that action to reduce demand 
for narcotics must be given overriding emphasis in the struggle 
against drugs 
as long as there is a demand for illicit drugs supplies will 
find their way to it the report said 
</TEXT>
