afghan soldiers used clubs and tree 
branches to flail cold hungry people who nearly engulfed soviet 
troopers distributing emergency rations in this blockaded city 
tuesday 
the blockade by moslem insurgents who have fought the communist 
regime for a decade has created acute shortages as the remaining 
50000 red army troops withdraw from afghanistan before the feb 15 
deadline set in a unmediated agreement 
a woman was pushed to the icy ground an afghan trooper with a 
rifle under his arm punched and kicked a group of teenagers when 
the crowd of about 1000 ignored repeated orders from the soviet 
soldiers shouting through megaphones to move back 
some afghan soldiers even swung blankets at men women and 
children who broke from waiting lines and pressed toward soviet 
armored personnel carriers that rolled into the rundown khairkhana 
district near the airport with emergency supplies of fuel 
five red army soldiers in fur hats were in each personnel 
carrier and they appeared ill at ease some sat staring at the 
crowd from their vehicles which were armed with 75mm cannons 
pointed skyward while others poured fuel into containers held up by 
people at the front of the line 
soviet soldiers made a similar distribution last week but the 
small amounts will be of little help 
i have nothing now my house is cold my children are hungry 
said a woman who identified herself as aziza a 35yearold mother 
of nine and never got to the head of the line 
a woman whose face was totally veiled according to strict moslem 
practice held out her hands to a western reporter and said my 
children are hungry i am hungry this is because the rebels are not 
letting supplies in 
children as young as 8 joined lines waiting for bread outside 
shacklike private bakeries in other parts of the capital shivering 
in predawn temperaturs far below freezing 
lines of buses and cars waiting for gasoline or diesel fuel 
stretched around entire blocks in downtown kabul 
western aid officials expressed alarm at the plight of 
malnourished children waiting for bread in frigid temperatures they 
said the government wheat silo for supplying private bakeries which 
holds 50000 tons and usually has a 40 percent reserve was 
virtually empty 
severe shortages began earlier this month when soviet forces 
started pulling out of the city and handing over convoy stations on 
the solang highway the vital route north to the governments 
unreliable conscript army a particuarly bitter winter exacerbates 
the lack of daily necessities 
as the crowd struggled toward the soviet supplies giant 
ilyushin76 transport planes took off reguarly from the airport a 
daily occurrence as the withdrawal deadline approaches 
afghans generally have been hostile to the soviet presence during 
the long civil war but some said tuesday they wanted the red army 
to stay if that meant getting some supplies 
soviet soldiers arrived in december 1979 and began leaving may 
15 1988 under the withdrawal accord they helped government forces 
combat the moslem guerrillas who began fighting after a communist 
coup in april 1978 and an estimated 115000 were in afghanistan 
when the agreement was signed 
no political settlement is in sight and the soviets have promised 
to continue arming afghan forces against the insurgents who were 
not a party to the withdrawal agreement and have continued fighting 
they are supported by the united states and pakistan afghanistans 
eastern neighbor 
unconfirmed reports circulated tuesday that the afghan army 
which usually gets its grain supplies from the soviets had been 
buying wheat on the private market 
food prices have more than doubled in four weeks flour has gone 
from 850 afghans the national currency for about 15 pounds to 
1700 afghans in a nation whose people earn an average of about 300 
afghans a month 
one us dollar buys 50 afghans at the official rate and 200 on 
the black market flourishing in kabuls bazaars 
an afghan doctor said there were no more of the special ration 
coupons that protected government employees against previous 
shortages 
