szoka defends the closings as necessary to maintain 82 viable 
churches and to help end a plantation mentality which he 
defined as white parish leaders running churches attended largely by 
blacks 
but for many black catholics who represent 4 percent of the 15 
million catholics in the archdiocese the church closing plan has 
showed them their place in the predominantly white church 
now that it has come down to economic strain with not a lot 
of employment money coming in we are the last to be thought of 
payton said monday 
black lay catholics with a vision a group formed to fight the 
closings said the diocese has angered blacks struggling to maintain 
the church in a city where 60 percent of the population is black 
this is a time when they should be trying to build more 
churches not close any down said marian gabriel cochairwoman 
of the group we are very angered by what supposedly has done us a 
favor 
at st philip neri church doris ann whigham worries about what 
will happen to the poor when her parish and the soup kitchen it 
operates closes in june 
a lot of people dont believe in god what is going to happen 
to them she asked 
they cant feel the love and warmth we give them at the 
church in affluent grosse point park that st philip neri is 
supposed to merge with 
but a black auxiliary bishop in the archdiocese supports szoka 
nobody is taking their lives away from them said bishop 
moses b anderson our religion is a religion of hope those who 
purvey it as something else are being unfaithful 
we have seen things terrible things weve seen profound 
changes he said and we can look at change in a positive way 
the black community has that faith and i think thats a gift 
the church in detroit is not alone 
msgr john tracy ellis a historian at the catholic university of 
america in washington said he thinks other cities that have seen 
large white catholic populations leave for the suburbs will have 
similar problems 
you could say the church has no control over it ellis said 
the archdiocese of new york tried to deal with too few catholics 
for too many parishes two decades ago when it established the 
interparish city finance corp spokesman joseph zwilling said 
the corporation lets wealthier churches help older poorer 
churches financially however ellis said cardinal john oconnor 
recently warned that several urban churches were suffering 
financially 
in chicago cardinal joseph bernardin issued a set of guidelines 
in 1987 to assist parishes in conducting a selfevaluation said the 
rev george sarauskas director of the office for research and 
planning for the archdiocese 
sarauskas said last year three black parishes working together 
consolidated and he said 10 other mostly black parishes are 
undergoing a planning process that likely will result in some 
closings and consolidations 
but some black catholics in detroit reject the official 
explanantions 
how can you say you are going to better something and then take 
away the facility the churches and the priests gabriel asked 
and when the church pulls out payton wonders what will be left 
behind 
you can very well accept other organizations and businesses 
pulling away if even the church is leaving 
