<TEXT>
the supreme court was urged tuesday to give 
states sweeping power to control child pornography by upholding a 
ban on nude depictions of children even by a parent 
its clear that posing a child in a state of nudity can and 
does do harm said attorney general james shannon of 
massachusetts the child will experience shame a fear of 
blackmail 
shannon appealed to the justices to reverse a massachusetts 
supreme judicial court ruling that threw out a state 
antipornography law on grounds it could make it a crime for parents 
to photograph their naked toddlers on the beach 
justice thurgood marshall picking up on that theme asked 
shannon what is wrong with taking a picture of a naked infant on a 
bear rug a pose familiar to millions 
those pictures are lawful shannon replied he said no 
prosecutor in massachusetts ever envisioned invoking the invalidated 
law to prevent that sort of activity 
some justices suggested they could dispose of the case without 
issuing a broad ruling dealing with the constitutionality of the 
law because massachusetts has replaced the statute with a narrower 
law 
the former law enacted in 1982 made it a crime to encourage or 
permit a child under 18 to pose or be exhibited in a state of 
nudity for purposes of a photograph picture or other visual 
reproduction even for private noncommercial use 
the massachusetts legislature has since revised the law to make 
such activity illegal only if done with lascivious intent 
shannon said the new law might not be strong enough to protect 
children from sexual abuse i can think of no obligation of the 
state that is more important he said 
he also said that while many states have laws against child 
pornography he believed only kansas and ohio had passed statutes as 
tough as the one struck down in massachusetts 
the massachusetts court ruling overturned the conviction of 
douglas oakes 40 of holden for taking photographs in 1984 of his 
14yearold stepdaughter while she posed topless clad only in a red 
scarf and bikini underwear on a bar in their home 
prosecutors said the girl later threw the photos in the woods and 
oakes made her retrieve them oakes was arrested after the girls 
mother went to police with the photos 
he was sentenced to 10 years in prison and was paroled after two 
years 
the massachusetts high court by a 43 vote said the law was too 
broad in restraining freedom of expression because it could make it 
a crime for a parent to take a snapshot of a naked oneyearold 
running on a beach or romping in a wading pool 
richard j vita oakes lawyer said tuesday the state has not 
offered proof of serious harm to minors from posing in the nude 
he said that the photographs at issue in the case are not 
pornographic and that the state was trying to outlaw an area of 
expression that is much a part of our culture 
some justices said the state does not have to prove harm to 
minors to outlaw such depictions 
justice antonin scalia questioned whether freedom of expression 
was at stake at all when a state makes it a crime to photograph 
someone in the nude 
i dont think youre talking about the first amendment even 
when one says parents should be free to photograph their naked 
infants on a bear rug scalia said thats a question of whether 
the state can intrude on the parentchild relationship 
the case is massachusetts vs oakes 871651 
