<TEXT>
there is general agreement in congress and 
among foreign policy experts that the bush administration should 
complete a ussoviet treaty on strategic arms negotiate 
reductions in conventional arms in europe and eliminate chemical 
weapons says a report released tuesday 
the report by the annapolis group a bipartisan think tank of 
politicians and policy experts said the incoming administrations 
top foreign policy priority should be the start treaty for reducing 
strategic arms 
the group also found overall support for retaining senior arms 
control negotiators paul nitze and max kampelman negotiating 
reductions in conventional arms in europe and elimination of 
chemical weapons and continuing star wars research at about current 
funding levels 
more than 125 members of congress current and former 
administration officials and foreign policy experts were interviewed 
for the project and the group said the report represented a 
consensus of views 
during a sixmonth period the group questioned among others 
rep les aspin dwis chairman of the house armed services 
committee secretary of the navy will ball senate minority leader 
bob dole rkan and brent scowcroft bushs nominee for national 
security adviser 
the report said bush will likely want to avoid conveying any 
sense of haste or urgency about completion of the start 
negotiation 
a sense of haste would be clearly counterproductive not only 
in terms of getting the best possible deal from the soviet union 
but in terms of securing senate consent to ratification as well 
it said 
but the report stressed the importance of continuing start 
negotiations and talks on conventional forces and chemical weapons 
noting that these efforts will advance your other interests in 
modernizing our strategic forces and in developing a strategic 
defense 
the start talks have been recessed since november bush said last 
month it was unlikely his new administration would be ready with 
proposals for the feb 15 date set by the reagan administration for 
continuation of the talks in geneva 
