<TEXT>
hundreds of peasants are running truckloads of 
grain across a provincial border in east china at breakneck speed in 
the dead of night to get top prices a state newspaper said tuesday 
the peasants daily said in a frontpage story that grainrunning 
across anhui provincial border into more prosperous neighboring 
provinces is dangerous but profitable because of low prices inside 
anhui 
officials in the border region have tried to prevent the grain 
outflow by setting up checkpoints to stop trucks but the paper said 
most trucks barrel past the checkpoints and elude pursuers in chases 
that have resulted in at least one death 
the paper criticized anhuis low grain prices and its checkpoints 
and warned such policies would only dampen peasants enthusiasm for 
planting grain at a time when grain harvests already are falling 
behind population growth 
in one accident along what it called the bloodstained grain 
road a 19yearold youth driving a grainladen truck lost control 
and crashed as he tried to speed past one checkpoint he was killed 
a few days earlier a checkpoint official who chased a speeding 
truck leaped onto its running board and punched his fist through the 
window to force the driver to stop the driver did not stop but the 
official suffered cuts and had to undergo surgery the paper said 
the grain truckers who make these deathdefying dashes are 
lured by the high prices outside anhui it wrote after a 
threemile dash they can earn more than 270 for their load but if 
they are stopped at the checkpoint they are fined 810 who wouldnt 
risk his life 
peasants must sell a fixed portion of their harvests directly to 
the state but supppsedly are allowed to sell the rest on the open 
market in any province 
officials in anhui however feared all the grain would flow to 
neighboring jiangsu fujian and guangdong where higher prices are 
offered the going price in jiangsu after the autumn harvest was 12 
cents a pound of unhusked rice compared with 96 cents a pound in 
anhui border area 
the relatively wealthy provinces of fujian and guangdong to the 
southeast offer even more the paper said both provinces have 
prosperous industrial and export sectors and generally attract much 
of the regions grain because of the high prices they can offer 
unhappy with anhuis low prices many peasants have withheld from 
sale an estimated 300000 tons of grain the paper noted this means 
they will have less ready cash for investing in next years crop 
it did not comment on the impact on grain supplies which are 
short in many parts of the country because of a poor harvest 
china harvested less than 393 million tons of rice wheat and 
other grains in 1988 down from nearly 403 million tons in 1987 
</TEXT>
