urban homelessness and hunger increased 
significantly in 1988 particularly among families with children 
the us conference of mayors said tuesday in reporting results of a 
survey of 27 major cities 
one of every four homeless persons in the surveyed cities was a 
child 
families women and children they make up the most 
significant increase we have experienced boston mayor raymond l 
flynn said in releasing the findings 
the conference which conducts an annual survey of hunger and 
homelessness reported that both had risen in nearly all of the 
cities it surveyed 
the senate budget committee chairman jim sasser dtenn 
speaking to the mayors later called the survey a devastating 
indictment of the neglect of the needs of our major urban centers 
he said the mayors had made a compelling case for increased spending 
on the problems 
flynn said the rate of increase seemed to have slowed a bit from 
the previous year in part because of increased emergency services 
provided by state and local governments 
officials in every city surveyed cited a lack of affordable 
housing as the main cause of homelessness and flynn blamed a sharp 
decline in federal spending on lowincome housing during the reagan 
admininistration 
shelters are not the answer flynn said permanent 
affordable housing that is the answer 
the survey was released at the opening of the annual winter 
meeting of the organization of bigcity mayors the survey was 
conducted among the 27 cities whose mayors sit on the conferences 
task force on hunger and homelessness headed by flynn 
among its findings were that in the past year in the surveyed 
cities 
requests for emergency shelter increased an average 13 percent 
all but two of the cities registered an increase 
requests for emergency food were up an average 19 percent 
threefifths of those asking for emergency food were memebers of 
families 
an average of 19 percent of the requests for emergency shelter 
went unmet and among homeless families the figure was 23 percent 
shelters in two out of three cities reported they turned away 
homeless families because of a lack of resources 
in 62 percent of the cities emergency food assistance 
facilities had to turn away people also for lack of resources 
on average the composition of the homeless population was 49 
percent single men 34 percent members of families 13 percent 
single women and the rest unaccompanied youth one in four was a 
child an average 34 percent of homeless were substance abusers and 
onefourth were severely mentally ill 23 percent had fulltime or 
parttime jobs 26 percent were veterans 
flynn called for more federal spending on urban problems and 
said he was encouraged by presidentelect bushs stated commitment 
to making homelessness a high priority 
the boston mayor said that by holding the increase in the defense 
budget to the inflation rate in the coming fiscal year an extra 4 
billion could be made avilable for lowincome housing and emergency 
shelter programs that would not solve the problem he said but 
could at least pay for emergency shelter programs and get started on 
increasing the availability of affordable housing 
