<TEXT>
a reagan administration lawyer on tuesday 
defended the governments attempt to label some political 
documentary films propaganda when approving their taxfree 
export saying the label is informative not disparaging 
but a lawyer for independent filmmakers told a federal appeals 
court that the labeling was an informal system of censorship 
the argument before the 9th us circuit court of appeals 
involved the us information agencys latest attempt to review 
thousands of documentaries each year for their content before 
approving them as educational scientific or cultural which 
allows their taxfree export under a treaty signed by 72 nations 
the agencys first regulations which rejected films that 
advocated viewpoints or were deemed to misrepresent a governments 
policy were declared unconstitutional by the 9th circuit last year 
the current regulations would require a film to be primarily 
factual in its approach to be based on a reasonably current 
state of available information and to acknowledge the existence 
of opposing viewpoints 
they would also allow the usia to tell other countries that a 
film though approved as educational was propaganda in that it 
was designed to promote a political religious or economic 
viewpoint the foreign government could then decide whether to 
approve taxfree imports 
the regulations were challenged by the makers of six documentary 
films four on subjects that include the dangers of uranium mining 
disarmanent and agent orange were denied usia approval one on 
drug use among urban youth had been rejected under the earlier 
standards but was approved under the new standards the sixth a 
sympathetic portrayal of the 1979 nicaraguan revolution was 
approved but given a propaganda label 
us district judge wallace tashima of los angeles rejected the 
new standards last may and ordered the usia to draft a third 
contentneutral set of standards while giving provisional approval 
to the films justice department lawyer wendy keats asked a 
threejudge panel tuesday to reverse tashimas ruling 
the 1954 treaty known as the beirut agreement requires 
governments to evaluate films based on their contents ms keats 
said she said the constitution does not prohibit a 
viewpointneutral assessment of whether a film is presented in a 
factual manner or a noncoercive statement that it is propaganda 
on its face the propaganda label does not either disparage a 
film or prevent it from being circulated ms keats said 
she said the label merely encourages foreign governments to take 
a second look at a film claims of censorship are unduly 
patronizing to foreign governments she said 
but the filmmakers lawyer david cole of the center for 
constitutional rights said the label was not simply neutral 
information but an attempt to get foreign governments to deny 
taxfree import of films that should qualify under the treaty he 
said canada has already declared that it would not accept us films 
with propaganda labels 
the usia has said they dont want these films to have 
benefits cole told the court he called the labeling an 
informal system of censorship 
us government propaganda labels on some imported films were 
allowed in 1986 by the supreme court which observed that the labels 
did not prevent anyone from seeing the films but cole said the 
current case is different because the labels are intended to stop 
foreign circulation of the films 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

