the sale of a california hightechnology 
company to a west german chemical firm is being reviewed by a 
government task force in the first test of a new law that allows the 
president to block foreign purchases of american companies on 
national security grounds 
the case involves the proposed sale of monsanto electronic 
materials of palo alto calif to huels ag of west germany 
the american company an operating division of the giant monsanto 
chemical company headquartered in st louis produces silicon 
wafers the flat discs used to make computer chips 
silicon wafers are the building blocks for the semiconductor 
industry a sector of the us economy considered vital not only for 
national security reasons but also for trade reasons americas edge 
in the battle with foreign competitors has centered in such 
hightechnology fields as computer manufacturing 
the proposed sale to the west german company was reviewed in a 
closeddoor meeting on tuesday by the committee on foreign 
investment the committee is composed of officials from eight 
government agencies and is headed by david c mulford an assistant 
treasury secretary 
the panel has until next monday to forward a recommendation to 
the president it is expected the proposed sale will be one of the 
first trade issues that presidentelect bush will have to face 
originally the commerce department and the defense department 
raised questions about the proposed sale however an attorney 
representing monsanto said tuesday he believes the original 
objections had been dealt with 
we have met with government officials on numerous occasions 
we answered all of the questions and repeat questions said 
washington lawyer joseph f dennin 
earle h harbison jr the president of monsanto and carl 
krauch the chairman of huels a subsidiary of the giant west german 
conglomerate veba ag both met with officials from various agencies 
on tuesday 
there is no credible evidence that huels an exemplary company 
from a nato ally would so something that would injure the national 
security of the united states dennin said 
officials at the commerce department said no announcement of the 
panels recommendation would be released before it was reviewed by 
the president who has 15 days under the law to reach a decision on 
the panels findings 
the review of foreign takeovers of us companies on national 
security grounds was included in the giant omnibus trade act of 
1988 congress had become concerned that the wave of foreign 
purchases of us companies could be endangering national security 
three other us producers of silicon wafers have been sold to 
