<TEXT>
the soviet union has agreed to foreign 
currency exchange with some east bloc allies and may lower its 
domestic exchange rates as a prelude to full convertibility in world 
markets an official said tuesday 
the deputy chairman of state bank of the ussr va pekshev 
told a unsponsored conference on ussoviet trade that soviet 
officials acknowledge the need for full convertibility of the ruble 
but must proceed slowly 
by jan 1 1990 we would make a 100 percent increase in the 
ratio of the official domestic exchange rate pekshev said in 
effect doubling the amount of rubles exchanged for other currencies 
is this a currency devaluation he said we wont get into 
theoretical arguments on this question 
the soviet union has several sets of exchange rates for domestic 
and foreign products and it was not known how the proposed increase 
would affect the rates black market exchange rates are often six to 
seven times higher than the official rates 
more than 100 americans and soviets including us and soviet 
envoys to the world body began the twoday meeting tuesday the 
first such conference held under un auspices 
us and soviet speakers focused mainly on soviet economic 
reforms and repeatedly expressed optimism about improving relations 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachevs policy of 
perestroika or restructuring has led to an explosion of 
cooperative business ventures and the relaxation of some 
restrictions on foreign trade 
but ventures have been stifled by the inconvertibility of the 
ruble in foreign exchange markets and by the need to operate through 
the soviet state bank which takes as much as 60 percent of hard 
currency earnings from each transaction 
western media have reported the possibility of changes in the 
official rate which currently brings about 160 per ruble one 
soviet official has said convertibility could result in a 10fold 
devaluation in the ruble 
pekshev dismissed the 10fold figure as speculative and said 
officials were considering ways to move to full convertibility 
stage by stage 
were not in a position today to assert a new value of the 
ruble to the dollar he said 
he said soviets have agreed to partial convertibility with 
several east european countries and were planning hard currency 
auctions for soviet and east bloc enterprises to buy the foreign 
currency needed for trade with the west foreign businesses 
initially will not be allowed to participate he said 
the conference is scheduled to end wednesday afternoon two days 
before presidentelect george bushs inauguration bush aides have 
said they are planning a wideranging review of us policy toward 
the soviet union before deciding on a new agenda for relations under 
bush 
exports to the united states jumped from 214 million in 1982 to 
446 million the next year and were projected to dip slightly to 
445 million in 1987 according to us figures us exports to the 
soviet union decreased from 34 billion in 1984 to a projected 13 
billion in 1987 
