<TEXT>
genesis music and miracles a retelling of 
five medieval mystery plays is not very musical and more mundane 
than miraculous 
this old testament song and dance which opened tuesday 
offbroadway at the new york shakespeare festival public theater 
sounds like it was spawned in the late 1960s the production has the 
earnestness but not the conviction of street theater the relentless 
beat but not the soaring melodies of such pop musicals as 
godspell and jesus christ superstar and the simplicity but 
not the charm of story theater 
five episodes are told in a quick 95 minutes the creation and 
the fall of lucifer the creation and fall of adam and eve the 
murder of abel noah and the flood and the story of abraham and 
isaac 
the results are painless and occasionally pleasant but nothing 
more the stories adapted by aj antoon and robert montgomery 
unfold in rhymes many of them awkward and forced the tales are so 
well known that they need a little passion humor and inventiveness 
to make them fly they dont get that here 
the best moments come in the story of noah and these are 
supplied by set designer john conklin who has given the actors 
boards and planks with which to construct a pretty spiffy ark the 
designer also supplies some toy animals wooden figures that are 
carried onto the boat by the actors 
for a musical the sparse score which has music by michael ward 
and lyrics by antoon and montgomery is surprisingly wispy sort of 
like the lesser love themes from the biblical movies of cecil b de 
mille 
still the large cast remains undefeated by the material 
particularly fine is stephen bogardus who plays the pivotal roles of 
adam noah and abraham bogardus has a booming musical comedy voice 
and is a fine actor if broadway had more than two or three musicals 
a year he always would find work mary mungers eve is sympathetic 
and forthright but shes also saddled with some of the worst lines 
as noahs shrewish wife 
in one novel bit of interpretation david patrick kelly plays 
cain almost like a psychotic street tough his murder of the 
passive almost nondescript abel is brutal unnerving and hard to 
watch 
the redhaired russ thacker makes a persuasive lucifer a 
grinning boyish sprite with a ghoulish smile special mention also 
should be made of young braden danner who sings in a clear crisp 
style and turns abrahams son isaac into a credible character and 
not just the plot device he usually is 
the choreography by lynne taylorcorbett doesnt get past minimal 
and is given mostly to two dancing doubles for adam and eve 
conklin also designed the costumes and they include what may be 
a first for the supposedly naked first couple anatomically 
correct fleshcolored body stockings a very strange coverup 
except for those inventive glad rags genesis music and 
miracles offers very little that is surprising or memorable once 
the house lights have gone back up 
</TEXT>
