<DOCNO> AP890117-0213 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a high school cannot allow students to hold 
regular religious meetings in a classroom shortly before the school 
day starts a federal appeals court ruled tuesday 
the ruling by the 9th us circuit court of appeals in a case 
from renton wash has implications for the equal access act a 
1984 federal law that requires public secondary schools to allow 
religious clubs to meet at school on the same basis as other 
extracurricular clubs 
the court stopped short of declaring the law unconstitutional 
saying instead that the renton school system wasnt affected by the 
law because it barred all noncurricular clubs from meeting on 
campus but the court also indicated that any oncampus religious 
meetings would probably violate the constitutional requirement of 
separation of church and state 
the district must exclude organized religious speech because 
use of public school facilities for religious purposes violates the 
establishment clause of the constitution which forbids a state 
establishment of religion said judge jerome farris in the 30 
decision 
if the ruling stands the equal access act has been 
functionally rendered impotent and wouldnt apply in virtually any 
public high school setting said steven mcfarland lawyer for a 
group of high school students in the seattle suburb he said he 
would appeal to the supreme court 
marc slonim a lawyer for the american civil liberties union of 
washington said the ruling may be the first by any federal appeals 
court on the issue but is consistent with a number of lowercourt 
decisions around the nation 
since early in the 19th century weve had a tradition of trying 
to separate religion from public schools so public schools can serve 
people of a wide variety of religious beliefs slonim said 
he described the equal access approach as an attempt to avoid 
the constitutional ban on preferential treatment of religion but 
said it inevitably sends a message of religious partisanship in 
the schools 
mcfarland said about 25 students applied in the fall of 1984 to 
use a classroom at lindbergh high school for beforeschool meetings 
of a nondenominational christian student group for religious and 
moral discussions bible readings and prayer 
the principal and school district denied the request citing 
constitutional standards as well as a district policy that allowed 
classroom meetings only if the purposes were an extension of a 
specific program or course offering the students also were 
rejected by us district judge walter mcgovern whose ruling was 
upheld tuesday 
permitting this student religious group to meet in a public 
high school just before the start of classes would impermissibly 
advance rather than neutrally accommodate religion farris said in 
the appeals court decision 
he said the meetings would take place at a time closely 
associated with a highly structured school day creating an 
appearance of school sponsorship 
although the supreme court in 1981 allowed a student religious 
group equal access to a universitys facilities the same standards 
do not apply to public high schools farris said 
high school students are required to attend school and are less 
mature and more impressionable than university students farris 
said teachers at high schools unlike college professors are 
both educators and authority figures 
he also said the meetings would improperly entangle the 
government with religion because teachers required by district 
policy to supervise all student activities on campus might either 
interfere with or advocate religious activities as the clubs 
supervisor 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

