the lawsuit filed jointly by lorene ellis helen goodsell and 
dianna smith contends their husbands deaths resulted from 
government negligence in implementing and monitoring safety 
standards at the mx facility 
specifically cited in the suit were the establishment and 
maintenance of mandatory criteria standards and methods for 
procedures involving the manufacturing of the mx motors 
the plaintiffs also claimed government negligence in holding 
regular inspections of the premises to ensure that procedures were 
being followed by morton thiokol and that the government neglected 
to warn employees or stop work in the event noncompliance was 
discovered 
the victims and two other thiokol employees had been manually 
removing the steel core from a casting of a firststage missile 
motor when 100000 pounds of solid rocket propellent ignited in a 
fireball dec 29 1987 at the companys wasatch operations plant 25 
miles west of brigham city 
four of the men were killed instantly and ellis died 11 hours 
later the air force said in a report three months after the 
accident that the fire was caused either by friction or static 
electricity 
the air force report concluded that morton thiokol had failed to 
provide an adequate remotecontrol system or fully implement other 
safety measures recommended after a near miss six months earlier 
that consisted of a flash and release of fumes during the same 
procedure 
a telephone call to the us attorneys office in salt lake city 
after business hours tuesday for comment on the suit was not 
answered 
morton thiokol was cited for six safety violations and fined 
31700 by the utah division of occupational safety and health the 
company vowed to appeal violations alleging serious and willful 
deviations from division rules but company spokesman rocky raab 
said tuesday he was not sure if the appeal was filed and the fine 
reduced 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

