<TEXT>
american mutual liability insurance co and 
american mutual insurance co were ordered by the state supreme 
court into receivership tuesday at the request of state insurance 
commissioner roger singer 
the action was prompted by concerns over the wakefield companies 
reserve capacity to cover primarily highrisk policies written in 
the 1960s and 1970s involving asbestos medical malpractice and 
toxic waste claims singer said 
under the order which was supported by the companies singer was 
named receiver and the companies were enjoined from issuing new 
policies or proceeding with their business except as permitted by 
singer 
the companies were authorized to continue paying automobile 
workers compensation and certain disability and accident and health 
claims but will not renew or write new policies 
the companies formed 101 years ago are licensed in all 50 
states but primarily operate in the northeast they have 20000 
commercial policies nationwide and nearly 75000 personal policies 
singer said the order was intended to protect policyholders while 
the insurance division works with management in an effort to 
improve the companies financial condition 
the insurance division will report back to the high court within 
30 days on whether to rehabilitate them in some ways or declare 
them insolvent singer said we will either have a plan to 
somehow get them back on their feet or well have the court declare 
them insolvent 
singer and company spokesman tom synder said there is a 
possibility that a portion of the companies may be sold 
national grange mutual insurance co of new hampshire has signed 
a letter of intent to buy a small stockcontrolled subsidiary of 
the companies american policyholders insurance co which is 
unaffected by the order although it too will stop writing new 
policies 
singer said national grange has expressed interest in buying 
american policyholders bringing 500 to 600 of american mutuals 
nearly 800 wakefield headquarters employees on board and paying off 
american mutuals longterm claims 
one of the big assets of this company american mutual is a 
welltrained experienced work force singer said 
synder said national grange will be reviewing the potential 
acquisition over the next 30 days 
in the meantime american mutual will be looking at cutting its 
total 1400employee work force to handle only claims synder said 
no decision on layoffs has been made yet 
singer said the companies reserve capacity has been under review 
by the insurance division since 1985 since then american mutual 
has brought in new management sold off assets and upgraded its 
business 
during the past several years the company has made great 
strides in strengthening its reserves to pay losses american 
mutual president j john wortman said the reserve accounts have 
been strengthened by over 250 million since 1986 
however some very recent changes in payment patterns on old 
losses indicate that even more reserves may be necessary he said 
singer said the discovery a few weeks ago of 500 million to 700 
million in potential longterm claim exposure prompted one investor 
interested in buying all three companies to back out and the 
insurance divisions decision to seek the receivership order 
synder said it was unclear what direction american mutual will 
take in 30 days but he said we obviously are not going to be 
the size or shape of company that we were in the past it all 
depends on what we can bring out of this 
</TEXT>
