a former international business machines corp 
employee who claims he was fired for refusing a transfer to south 
africa has filed a 25 million lawsuit against the computer giant 
victor s khabo a black naturalized us citizen born in 
pretoria south africa claimed he balked at the transfer to south 
africa because he still faces charges for his antiapartheid 
activities there 
a former ibm marketing representative khabo sued the armonk 
nybased company earlier this week at federal court in manhattan 
accusing ibm of alleged unlawful employment practices 
on tuesday however an ibm spokeswoman disputed khabos claim 
the termination was not related to south africa south africa 
was not an issue said theo chisholm in a telephone interview 
ibm announced plans to sell its south african holdings to 
employees there in october 1986 ms chisholm said that as of march 
1987 ibm had no assets or employees in south africa 
she declined to say more adding we dont comment on cases 
that are in litigation 
according to khabos lawsuit he was hired by ibm in june 1984 
and a year later was asked to join south african students being 
trained to work at ibms division in south africa 
but khabo a new brunswick nj resident with masters degrees 
in economics and business administration claimed he told company 
officials that he couldnt go back to his homeland unless the 
political system there changed 
in 1963 when he was 16 according to the lawsuit khabo was 
twice arrested as a leader in the african student association he 
was released the first time but sentenced to 21 months hard labor 
the second time 
in 1975 according to court papers khabo who already was 
living in the united states was named a coconspirator in an 
alleged 1963 plot to overthrow the south african government 
khabo claimed that after he refused the transfer to south africa 
he was passed over for assignment to a sales territory and was 
denied funds for courses to complete his doctorate despite previous 
company promises to do so 
in addition to ibm the lawsuit named four of khabos former 
managers and ibm chairman john f akers as codefendants 
